When a `null` value is used in a value comparison as part of the predicate of `findIndex`, the returned index is incorrect.

I reviewed #2119 and #3344 (discussion of behavior when `findIndex` lacks an `iteratee`) but this is a bit different.

In the example below, `null < o.max` seems to evaluate to `true`:

```jsx
var users = [
  { 'user': 'barney',  'max': 2 },
  { 'user': 'fred',    'max': 4 },
  { 'user': 'pebbles', 'max': 6 }
];

_.findIndex(users, (o) =>  1 < o.max);
// => 0 (OK)

_.findIndex(users, (o) =>  6 < o.max);
// => -1 (OK)

_.findIndex(users, (o) =>  null < o.max);
// => 0 (EXPECTED: -1)

_.findIndex(users, (o) =>  null < o.max || null);
// => 0 (EXPECTED: -1)

_.findIndex(users, (o) =>  null < o.max && o.max === 4);
// => 1 (EXPECTED: -1)

_.findIndex(users, (o) =>  null);
// => -1 (OK)
```

